Correlation Maps

# Pearson correlation matrix
pearson_corr <- cor(selected_data %>% select_if(is.numeric), method = "pearson", use = "complete.obs")

# Spearman correlation matrix
spearman_corr <- cor(selected_data %>% select_if(is.numeric), method = "spearman", use = "complete.obs")

pearson_melted <- melt(pearson_corr)
spearman_melted <- melt(spearman_corr)

                                  list = FALSE,

test_data  <- selected_data[-trainIndex,]

##Descriptive analysis

# Filter only numeric columns
numeric_data <- selected_data %>% select(where(is.numeric))

# Calculate mean and standard deviation for numeric columns
mean_sd <- numeric_data %>%
  summarise(across(
    everything(),
    list(Mean = ~mean(.x, na.rm = TRUE), SD = ~sd(.x, na.rm = TRUE))
  ))

# Reshape the result into a clean table with rounded values
mean_sd_table <- data.frame(
  Variable = colnames(numeric_data),
  Mean = round(as.numeric(mean_sd[1, seq(1, ncol(mean_sd), 2)]), 2),
  SD = round(as.numeric(mean_sd[1, seq(2, ncol(mean_sd), 2)]), 2)
)

# Print the final table
print(mean_sd_table)

    Mean = mean(DAYS_BIRTH, na.rm = TRUE),
    `3rd Quartile` = quantile(DAYS_BIRTH, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE),
    Maximum = max(DAYS_BIRTH, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

# Calculate counts and proportions for selected categorical variables
demographic_stats <- selected_data %>%
  select(CODE_GENDER, NAME_FAMILY_STATUS, OCCUPATION_TYPE) %>%
  mutate(
    CODE_GENDER = ifelse(CODE_GENDER == "M", "Male", 
                         ifelse(CODE_GENDER == "F", "Female", "Other"))
  ) %>%
  summarise(
    Gender = list(table(CODE_GENDER) %>% as.data.frame()),
    Relationship_Status = list(table(NAME_FAMILY_STATUS) %>% as.data.frame()),
    Occupation = list(table(OCCUPATION_TYPE) %>% as.data.frame())
  )

# Convert into a readable format
gender_stats <- demographic_stats$Gender[[1]] %>%
  mutate(Proportion = Freq / sum(Freq) * 100)

relationship_stats <- demographic_stats$Relationship_Status[[1]] %>%
  mutate(Proportion = Freq / sum(Freq) * 100)

occupation_stats <- demographic_stats$Occupation[[1]] %>%
  mutate(Proportion = Freq / sum(Freq) * 100)

##Visualizations

# Create a data frame for gender statistics
gender_data <- data.frame(
  Category = c("Female", "Male", "Other"),
  Proportion = c(69.17, 30.83, 0.003)
)

# Create a data frame for family status statistics
family_status_data <- data.frame(
  Category = c("Civil marriage", "Married", "Separated", "Single / not married", "Widow"),
  Proportion = c(9.91, 62.83, 7.47, 16.28, 3.51)
)

# Pie chart for gender
ggplot(gender_data, aes(x = "", y = Proportion, fill = Category)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  labs(title = "Gender Proportions", fill = "Gender") +
  theme_void()

# Pie chart for family status
ggplot(family_status_data, aes(x = "", y = Proportion, fill = Category)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  labs(title = "Family Status Proportions", fill = "Family Status") +
  theme_void()

# Filter numeric variables
numeric_variables <- c("DAYS_BIRTH", "AMT_INCOME_TOTAL", "AMT_CREDIT")

# Convert TARGET to a factor with clear labels
selected_data1 <- selected_data %>%
  mutate(TARGET = factor(TARGET, labels = c("No Default", "Default")))

# Loop through each numeric variable and create boxplots
for (var in numeric_variables) {
  # Create the boxplot
  plot <- ggplot(selected_data1, aes(x = TARGET, y = .data[[var]], fill = TARGET)) +
    geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA, alpha = 0.7) + # Exclude extreme outliers
    scale_y_continuous(limits = quantile(selected_data[[var]], c(0.01, 0.99), na.rm = TRUE)) + # Adjust y-axis to focus on main data
    labs(
      title = paste("Comparison of", var, "by TARGET"),
      x = "Target Status",
      y = var,
      fill = "Target"
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = "none") # Remove legend as TARGET is labeled on x-axis

  # Print the plot
  print(plot)
}
